# Match-Day Weather + Player Nationality Climate Disadvantage Analysis

## Overview

Two new intelligent features layered on top of the already-working Opponent Weakness pipeline:

1. **Match-Day Weather Forecast** — Use OpenWeatherMap's 5-day/3-hour forecast endpoint (`/forecast`) with the stadium's exact `lat`/`lng` (already in `stadiums.json`) to get the predicted conditions for the chosen **Game Date + Match Time** saved in Settings.
2. **Nationality × Climate Disadvantage Analysis** — For every opponent player, read their `birthArea` from `players (1).json`, map it to a climate zone (tropical, cold, arid, etc.), compare it to the forecast conditions at the stadium, and let Gemini flag players who are likely at a physiological/psychological disadvantage.

Both features feed into the **Opponent Weakness** player cards already displayed in the Pregame screen. A new filter chip **"Climate Disadvantage"** and a new weather banner will surface the data without changing the existing UI contract.

---

## Open Questions

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **OpenWeather API key placement** — the key `f3d58e99dd52bd40e33fbf9d54a5ba54` must be added to `cloud_run/.env` as `OPENWEATHER_API_KEY`. It is currently missing (only `GOOGLE_API_KEY` is present).

> [!NOTE]
> **Forecast window** — OpenWeatherMap `/forecast` gives forecasts every 3 hours up to **5 days ahead**. If the match date is set more than 5 days away, we will fall back to **current weather** from `/weather` and note the limitation. No user action needed; handled automatically.

> [!NOTE]
> **Birth-area climate mapping** — We will use a **static country → Köppen climate zone** lookup table (~60 countries cover all players in the dataset). This avoids extra API calls and is fast. Gemini then interprets the mismatch between that zone and the match-day forecast.

